data.content:
Here are the four breaking changes and their fixes:

---

### 1. `GenericShift.cs` — Consistent shift behavior in generic math

In .NET 9, generic shift operations on small types (`byte`, `short`, etc.) were **inconsistent** — e.g. `ShiftLeft<byte>(0xFF, 8)` returned `0` because the shift amount wasn't masked. In .NET 10, shift operations are now **consistent** across all types, masking the shift amount to the type's bit width (`& 7` for `byte`). So `ShiftLeft<byte>(0xFF, 8)` now returns `0xFF` (8 & 7 = 0, no shift). If you relied on the old overflow-to-zero behavior, add explicit bounds checks:

```csharp
static T ShiftLeft<T>(T value, int amount) where T : IShiftOperators<T, int, T>, IBinaryInteger<T>
{
    int bitWidth = T.GetByteCount() * 8;
    if (amount >= bitWidth) return T.Zero;
    return value << amount;
}
```

---

### 2. `ApiClient.cs` — Streaming HTTP responses enabled by default in browser

In .NET 10 Blazor WASM, **streaming HTTP responses are enabled by default**. Previously the response was fully buffered before `ReadAsStreamAsync()` returned. Now the stream delivers data incrementally, meaning your **synchronous `stream.Read()`** may return partial data or zero bytes before the response is complete. Fix: use async reads:

```csharp
var stream = await response.Content.ReadAsStreamAsync();
var ms = new MemoryStream();
await stream.CopyToAsync(ms);           // async, handles streaming
byte[] data = ms.ToArray();
// or read in a loop:
int bytesRead = await stream.ReadAsync(buffer);
```

---

### 3. `Archiver.cs` — PaxTarEntry no longer sets atime/ctime by default

In .NET 10, `PaxTarEntry` **no longer populates `AccessTime` and `ChangeTime` by default**. They will be `DateTimeOffset.MinValue` (or omitted) unless explicitly set. Fix:

```csharp
var now = DateTimeOffset.UtcNow;
var entry = new PaxTarEntry(TarEntryType.RegularFile, "data.txt");
entry.AccessTime = now;
entry.ChangeTime = now;
archive.WriteEntry(entry);
```

---

### 4. `App.csproj` + HTTP/3 — HTTP/3 stripped by trimmer

With `<PublishTrimmed>true</PublishTrimmed>`, **HTTP/3 support is completely disabled** in .NET 10 — the trimmer removes the HTTP/3 implementation code entirely. Your backend connections will silently fall back to HTTP/2 or HTTP/1.1. Fix: add `Http3Support` to your project file:

```xml
<PropertyGroup>
  <PublishTrimmed>true</PublishTrimmed>
  <Http3Support>true</Http3Support>
</PropertyGroup>
```
